data.name: Label95.Text
data.value:
This panel allows you to customise your preference with regards to the MPAA movie rating or Cert.
Since not all movies are listed with all certificates, Media Companion will use the first available certificate in the order you select below

data.name: Label104.Text
data.value: The settings for local actors can be tricky and if you dont know what you are doing it is recommended that you leave this feature disabled. The only negative effects are a slightly slower browsing speed for Media Companion, and scraping by XBMC will also be a little slower (If you have enabled actor thumbs).

data.name: Label103.Text
data.value: The "XBMC path" needs to be to the same folder as above, but from where XBMC is installed. If XBMC is installed on the same machine as Media Companion then the paths will be the same, but if XBMC is located on a seperate network device then the path will need to be as it is from XBMC to the Actor folders. The folder will need to be shared, and have any user and password information included in the path. eg "smb://username:password@devicename/sharename/"

data.name: Label101.Text
data.value: Under normal circumstances, Media Companion will include the internet location for each available actor thumbnail. There are a couple of problems with this, firstly, when XBMC scrapes each nfo, if you enable actor thumbnails, XBMC needs to download these from the internet. Secondly, since MC also uses these urls to display actor thumbs, it can slow down the Media Companion browser. These settings allow you to override this behaviour, saving the actor thumbs to a local folder, and adding the path to this into the nfo instead of a url.

Using multisave mode it is possible to edit multiple movies at the same time,
This can be any editable field including sets, and clicking the save button will save the new details to all selected movies.
If you do not wish to edid a field then leave it blank, only fields that contain text will be changed.

data.name: Label68.Text
data.value: Use this page to edit what movie sets are available. These sets can be used to group collections of movies together within XBMC, eg. If you were to add the movie set "Star Wars Collection", and make all Star Wars movies part of this set, then they would be added to the XBMC library as "Star Wars Collection" Selecting this in XBMC would list all these movies..

data.name: Label86.Text
data.value:
Add your movie folders from this location.
Your movies can be organised however you please, and MC uses a recursive search method so subfolders will be checked. i.e. 'C:/Movies/' Would allow MC to find any movies located within the "Movies" folder, and all of its subfolders.

data.name: Label87.Text
data.value:
If you have removed or added folders then use the "Save && Quick Refresh" button to save the folders and update the movie list.
Once folders have been added and saved, use the "Search for new movies" tab to allow MC to find and scrape any located media

data.name: Label136.Text
data.value:
Offline Movie Folders are a feature of Media Companion that allows your DVD/Blu-Ray Collection to be added to your library without it being stored on your system.
To add an offline movie, create a folder in one of your selected offline movie folders and label it as the title of the movie it represents. eg: \Offline Movie Folder\Star Trek. When Media Companion searches for new movies it will search for the movie and add the appropriate nfo, tbn, and fanart to the folder, it will also create a 16 second movie clip from the fanart that asks you to insert the Appropriate Disk.
The search for offline movies is not recursive, so make sure the folders you want added are in one of your offline movie folder roots.

data.name: Label99.Text
data.value: Media Companion can attempt to automatically download a Poster when a movie is first scraped, if this option is enabled, then the setting below allows you to prioritise the order that sources are checked for an available poster.

data.name: Label56.Text
data.value: If one of the above TV Shows is the correct one, then select your preferred options from the panel opposite, and select scrape. If none of the above are correct, then alter the search term and search again.

data.name: Label81.Text
data.value:
Root Folders are folders that contain multiple TV Shows
For example :- D:/Root/TV Show 1 D:/Root/TV Show 2 You would add the path: D:/Root
Folders added to this list can be checked for new TV Show folders and can be added to the Seperate Folders List automatically on startup.
To check for new TV Folders when the program is running, use the "Check Roots for New TV Shows" menu item, located in the "TV Shows" drop down menu.

data.name: Label84.Text
data.value:
Seperate folders are those that contain only a single TV Show
For Example :- D:/Root/TV Show 1 You would add the path: D:/Root/TV Show 1
Adding shows using this method means that all shows must be added manually.

data.name: Label138.Text
data.value:
If you have enabled the option to 'Save Actor Thumbs to the '.Actors' Folder' located in the general preferences then this gives you this additional option. When Scraping episodes from TVDB, the only actor thumbnails avaialble are those at IMDB, but compared to TVDB, these actor thumbs are low quality.
This preference gives you the option to copy an actors thumb, if available, to the episodes actor folder, allowing the higher quality TVDB actor thumb to be used for the episode.

data.name: Label139.Text
data.value: Enabling the 'Quick Add' option will speed up the scraping of TV Shows by not downloading available Art. All show art can be scraped at any time by using the TV context menu item to 'Download missing art'

data.name: Label140.Text
data.value: Media Companion now offers the option to automatically rename episodes during scraping. Only use this option if you are sure that the media file is named according to supported MC naming conventions.

data.name: Label166.Text
data.value:
Add your Home Movie folders from this location.
Your movies can be organised however you please, and MC uses a recursive search method so subfolders will be checked. i.e. 'C:/Movies/' Would allow MC to find any movies located within the "Movies" folder, and all of its subfolders.

data.name: Label157.Text
data.value: The default behaviour is for MC to overwrite none compliant nfo files, you can change this below. If you turn this off, MC will not overwrite existing conflicting nfo's && as such will not add those files.

data.name: Label115.Text
data.value: Media Companion can be used to playback media files, Use the options below to select what program you want to use for playback. To allow playback of multi-part media files, Media Companion creates a m3u playlist.

data.name: Label141.Text
data.value:
Use this Panel to Add Custom Commands to MC. It can be used to start an XBMC Update, or maybe just to launch an external program.
The commands will be listed by their title within the 'Tools' drop down menu
Each Command must have a unique 'Title'

data.name: Label149.Text
data.value:
DB Export Page
You can use this tab to export the entire MC database into an xml file that can be imported by XBMC. There are a number of advantages of this approach, firstly this method is much faster than using XBMC scrapers to read the nfo files, and secondly, additional information, such as watched status will be included.
